Forest Removal

David Clark

July 3, 2016

In this project I investigate the relationship between forest removal and percent forest coverage for countries in the world. Forest removal is defined as the total value in US dollars of all products removed during that year. Products are both wood and non-wood related. All data is taken from the Gapminder website.

Data Processing and Exploration

Let’s load the data and inspect it.

forestCoverage = read.csv("data/forest_coverage.csv", header = TRUE)
forestRemoval = read.csv("data/forest_products_per_ha.csv", header = TRUE, na.strings = "")

Let’s view the column names:

names(forestCoverage)
## [1] "Forest.coverage...." "X1990"               "X2000"              
## [4] "X2005"               "X"                   "X.1"                
## [7] "X.2"                 "X.3"                 "X.4"
names(forestRemoval)
## [1] "Forest.products.per.ha..USD." "X2005"                       
## [3] "X"                            "X.1"                         
## [5] "X.2"                          "X.3"                         
## [7] "X.4"

I am only interested in the columns with data containing the country name and data for a specific year. Therefore, I am interested in columns 1 - 4 for forerstCoverage and columns 1 - 2 for forestRemoval.

forestCoverage = forestCoverage[1:4]
forestRemoval = forestRemoval[1:2]

Let’s rename the columns so that they are more readable:

colsForestCoverage = c("Country", "fc_1990", "fc_2000", "fc_2005")
colnames(forestCoverage) = colsForestCoverage

colsForestRemoval = c("Country", "fr_2005")
colnames(forestRemoval) = colsForestRemoval

In the forestRemoval data frame, the values in the fr_2005 column are factors. I need to convert them to numeric, so that I can perform a linear regression fit:

forestRemoval$fr_2005 = as.numeric(levels(forestRemoval$fr_2005))[forestRemoval$fr_2005]
## Warning: NAs introduced by coercion

Now, let’s view some metrics using summary():

summary(forestCoverage)

You will notice that there are many points that are NAs These are missing data values and I want to remove them from the analysis. I do this with the following commands:

forestCoverage = na.omit(forestCoverage)
forestRemoval = na.omit(forestRemoval)

Since I am interested in the relationship between forest removal and forest coverage, I need to compare each dataframe equally. This means, I am only interested in countries that have data for both forest removal and forest coverage. To ensure this, I will merge the two dataframes into one dataframe using country to connect the two.

forestMerged = merge(forestCoverage, forestRemoval, by='Country')

Now I attach the columns to the dataframe so I can reference the columns by column name:

attach(forestMerged)

Before modeling the data, let’s use ggplot to make a scatterplot of forest removal versus forest coverage for the year 2005. This is the only year where data exists for both set’s of measurements.

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(forestMerged, aes(x=fc_2005, y=fr_2005)) +
        labs(title = 'Forest Removal', x='Forest Coverage (%)', y='Forest Removal') +
        geom_point()

Right off you will notice a wide scatter. Specifically, there is a larger scatter in forest removal for low values of forest coverage.

Linear Regression

Now I am ready to start modeling the data.

First, I fit a linear regression model to this dataset to see what is the relationship between forest coverage and forest removal.

lm.fit = lm(fr_2005 ~ fc_2005, data=forestMerged)

coef(lm.fit)
## (Intercept)     fc_2005 
##  138.678611   -1.604558

The negative coefficient for fc_2005 indicates that there is an inverse relationship between forest coverage and forest removal.

Let’s look at the fit in more detail.

summary(lm.fit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = fr_2005 ~ fc_2005, data = forestMerged)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -135.64  -76.06  -39.93   16.06  668.28 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 138.6786    26.5635   5.221 9.85e-07 ***
## fc_2005      -1.6046     0.6773  -2.369   0.0198 *  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 149.6 on 99 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.05366,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.0441 
## F-statistic: 5.613 on 1 and 99 DF,  p-value: 0.01977

Here the small R-squared value and an F-statistic with a value greater than one indicate a reasonable model fit.

Can the model be improved by using a non-linear fit? Let’s take the log of forest removal and see how things change:

lm.fit = lm(log(fr_2005) ~ fc_2005, data=forestMerged)
summary(lm.fit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = log(fr_2005) ~ fc_2005, data = forestMerged)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -3.7361 -1.4395  0.1067  1.3487  3.1296 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)  3.758526   0.308261  12.193   <2e-16 ***
## fc_2005     -0.017635   0.007859  -2.244   0.0271 *  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.736 on 99 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.0484, Adjusted R-squared:  0.03879 
## F-statistic: 5.035 on 1 and 99 DF,  p-value: 0.02707

Now F-statistic and R-squared values have improved by almost a factor of two. Clearly adding a log term has improved the model fit.

To investigate this model fit further, let’s compute confidense intervals. This is done using the function confint():

confint(lm.fit)
##                  2.5 %       97.5 %
## (Intercept)  3.1468690  4.370183990
## fc_2005     -0.0332301 -0.002040822

We can also compute the confidense interval at several points using the predict() function. I choose the percent forest coverage values of 20, 40, 60, and 80:

predict(lm.fit, data.frame(fc_2005=c(20, 40, 60, 80)), interval = 'confidence')
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 3.405817 3.011613 3.800021
## 2 3.053108 2.690861 3.415355
## 3 2.700399 2.151214 3.249583
## 4 2.347689 1.531272 3.164107

As expected, the fit decreases for larger values of forest coverage. You will also notice that the confidense interval ranges in width from ~70 to 140. This could be because the are fewer points for larger values of forest coverage, which makes it harder for the model to make a good fit.

I now replot the scatter plot and add the regression line. I use geom_smooth() to add the regression line and include the confidense region on either side of the line.

ggplot(forestMerged, aes(x=fc_2005, y=fr_2005)) +
        labs(title = 'Forest Removal', x='Forest Coverage (%)', y='Forest Removal') +
        geom_point() +
        geom_smooth(method = lm)

Now we can graphically see that there is a downward trend in the model fit. This indicates that countries with more forest tend to remove less wood. But, why does this trend exist? Are there other factors that contribute to forest removal? To investigate, let’s add additional features and see how this affects the model fit.

Adding Features

One reason countries with more forest might remove less wood is because they have a smaller population. Let’s add population as an additional feature and see what we find.

Load the data:

population = read.csv('data/population.csv', header = TRUE)
attach(population)

Since I am only modeling data from 2005, I am only interested in the population for that year:

population = population[c('Total.population', 'X2005')]

Rename the columns:

colsPopulation = c("Country", "p_2005")
colnames(population) = colsPopulation

Merge population dataframe with forestMerged dataframe:

forestPopMerged = merge(forestMerged, population, by="Country")
attach(forestPopMerged)
## The following objects are masked from forestMerged:
## 
##     Country, fc_1990, fc_2000, fc_2005, fr_2005

Performing a summary() on the forestPopMerged dataframe, we see that p_2005 is of type other. We need to set this to a numeric value:

forestPopMerged$p_2005 = as.numeric(levels(forestPopMerged$p_2005))[forestPopMerged$p_2005]

Add population feature
